SIMPLE: diamine
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Diamine
<hw>Di*am"ine</hw> <pr>(?; 104)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>di-</ets> + <ets>amine</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A
compound containing two amido groups united with one or more basic or
positive radicals, -- as contrasted with a <xex>diamide</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In chemical nomenclature, if any amine or diamine is
named by prefixing the nitrogen group, the name of the latter takes the
form of <xex>amido</xex>, <xex>diamido</xex>, etc., thus <xex>ethylene
diamine</xex>, <chform>C2H4.(NH2)2</chform>, is also called
<xex>diamido-ethylene</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Diamond</ent>⟦br⟧
